    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Formal vs. Informal Address",
      "explanation": "Croatian distinguishes between formal and informal speech. Use 'ti' (you, informal) with friends and young people, and 'Vi' (you, formal) with strangers, elders, and in professional settings. Verbs change accordingly: 'Kako si?' (informal) vs. 'Kako ste?' (formal). When in doubt, use the formal form - Croatians appreciate politeness from foreigners.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "How are you? (informal)",
          "target_primary": "Kako si?",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "How are you? (formal)",
          "target_primary": "Kako ste?",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "Thank you (more polite/emphatic)",
          "target_primary": "Hvala lijepa",
          "target_alt": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Croatian Greetings Culture",
      "content": "Croatians greet each other warmly. 'Bok' is the most common informal greeting in Zagreb and northern Croatia, used for both hello and goodbye - similar to Italian 'ciao'. In Dalmatia (the coast), you may hear 'Bog' instead. When meeting someone for the first time, a firm handshake is standard. Close friends and family often greet with kisses on both cheeks. Croatians generally use formal address ('Vi') until invited to switch to informal ('ti'), a transition called 'tikanje' which signals a closer relationship."
    }
